Orbcomm: Devices + Network + Apps = Internet Of Things - ORBCOMM Inc. (NASDAQ:ORBC) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Orbcomm: Devices + Network + Apps = Internet Of ThingsAug.31.16 | About: ORBCOMM Inc. (ORBC) Gary Milne Special situations, Growth, long-term horizonSummaryRecent deals with CIMC, Maersk and Carrier demonstrate a pivotal point in market evolution.Food Safety Management Act creating large wave of opportunity in refrigerated shipping and distribution.Satellite launch risk is removed and satellite network capacity has increased 10X.Very impressive portfolio of satellite and cellular partners, hardware products, SaaS solutions and industry leading customers.Verizon showing interest in Internet of Things solution players. Introduction Long before the "Internet of Things" became a technology term and investing buzzword Orbcomm (NASDAQ:ORBC) was connecting terrestrial objects such as shipping containers and construction equipment (things) to the internet via its satellite network. Orbcomm is perceived as a satellite company but really has 3 things to sell.  Devices that send status message over a network. Two way communications over their satellite or partner cellular network. A range of industry specific Software as a Service applications.  Putting these three things together and we get Devices + Network + Apps. Think that over for a minute! Devices that communicate over a network to software that monitors/reports/changes based on what it sees. That sounds like a dictionary definition for the Internet of Things. However, Orbcomm is largely seen as a satellite company with a small subscriber network when in fact it is at the nexus of three technologies that are all central to the IoT revolution. IoT devices, networking and SaaS solutions. Read on to see why I believe Orbcomm is poised to rapidly grow their subscriber and enterprise solutions base over the 1-2 years, especially in the areas of shipping and distribution. This article does not evaluate the present financials of Orbcomm or make estimates on future share price. The goal is to evaluate the company and the potential market for their goods and services. Orbcomm's Background Orbcomm has a long history dating back to its origins as Orbital Sciences Inc. in 1993 and has operated a satellite network since 2000. In 2001, it was acquired by new ownership and became a public company in 2006. Through a process of organic growth and an aggressive acquisition strategy, ORBC now has 1.6M+ subscribers and expects annual revenues for 2016 around $200M. 

 ORBC Revenue (Annual) data by YCharts Revenue Sources Hardware: These are the communication devices that gather data from a physical object on the ground and transmit the data to the nearest orbiting satellite (or via cellular). Hardware accounts for about 45% of their revenue. Network Services: Orbcomm has over 1.2M subscribers for their network services. Subscribers pay a monthly fee to use the Orbcomm network which includes their own satellite or partner terrestrial cellular networks. Enterprise Solutions: Orbcomm has 450,000 subscribers to their enterprise solutions which provide turnkey SaaS applications to companies in the transportation and distribution business (trucking, shipping and intermodal) as well as solutions for heavy equipment and SCADA system. Remember, Devices + Network + Apps = Internet of Things The Orbcomm Network December 2015 saw the completed launch of 11 new OG2 satellites, bringing the total to 17 OG2 satellites and 25 OG1 satellites, which are still operating after 17 years in service. Each OG2 satellite has the capacity of 12 OG1 satellites and also supports much larger message sizes. Improvements in the OG2 satellites allow the terrestrial devices to be smaller and use less power. The successful launch of these satellites was a large risk that has now been eliminated. In addition to the 42 Orbcomm owned satellites, Orbcomm also has agreements with Inmarsat and Globalstar to ensure global coverage even in countries such as China and Russia where licenses are almost impossible to obtain. In addition to satellite modems, Orbcomm also sells cellular and dual mode devices to accommodate the broadest range of a customer's need. The Orbcomm cellular solution works with: AT&T, Verizon, T-Mobile, Orange, Rogers, Telefonica and Vodafone. The global network is built, the biggest risk is off the table and network capacity has increased at least ten-fold. The network is ready to scale up dramatically from its 1.2 million network subscribers with minimal incremental capex investment. The Orbcomm Solution Orbcomm provides a global solution that allows its customers to monitor any kind of asset regardless of its physical location. The main uses at present are:  Transportation: Trailers, shipping containers, fleet and driver management, intermodal containers. Sample customers are Wal-Mart, CIMC, Maersk, Carrier, Union Pacific, Hub Group. Heavy Equipment: Construction and agriculture. Sample customers are John Deere, Komatsu, Caterpillar, Hyundai, Volvo. Monitoring and Control: Remote industrial infrastructure such as Oil and Gas, Electrical grid, water and waste management.  A simple example: A refrigerated container carries perishable goods. With an Orbcomm solution, the container can continuously transmit information such as location, temperature, humidity, power, fuel, door open/close events to a central monitoring station. Should the temperature go outside specified limits, a technician can be dispatched to resolve the issue before the load spoils. The Opportunity In Shipping InterModal Containers The global capacity for intermodal shipping containers in 2012 was estimated to be 34 million TEU. A TEU is a Twenty Foot Equivalent container so a 40 foot container = 2 TEU. While the exact number of containers is unknown, 25 million is a reasonable estimate. In 2015, the new container capacity added was estimated at 3 million TEU and another 2 million TEU for replacement of lost/damaged/retired containers. This places the number of new containers built each year at 2-3 million containers. China International Marine Corp. is the world's largest builder of containers (China produces ~90% of world supply) estimated to be around 50% of the world supply, or approximately 1.25 million units each year. In November of 2015, CIMC selected Orbcomm to build an OEM solution for CIMC which went into testing in early 2016. The potential opportunity here is huge relative to their current subscriber base. Refrigerated Containers (Reefers) Maersk, one the largest shippers in the world, has a fleet of over 260,000 refrigerated containers (referred to as reefers in the industry). In May 2016, the COO of Maersk went public on their decision to retrofit their entire reefer fleet with remote monitoring in a 5-year project. Today, 59% of the claims made against Maersk relate to failures of reefer units so they have a strong economic incentive to solve this problem. Orbcomm subsidiary WAM Technologies (acquired 2015) supplied the telematics application and device management middleware for the final solution. Orbcomm's ReeferConnect solution is now deployed on over 300,000 reefer containers worldwide and are managed via their ReeferConnect SaaS application. The Opportunity in Distribution There are estimated to be 15.5 million trucks in the US alone. Approximately, 2 million of these are semis with about 5.6 million accompanying semi trailers. Many of these trucks and semis form part of commercial fleets and Orbcomm has established a very strong position in refrigerated trucking and a competitive position in dry van fleet management. Orbcomm's reefer customer list reads like a who's who of the refrigerated trucking industry including C.R. England, Werner, Carrier, Celadon, Marten, Prime Inc., Swift, Tyson, Wal-Mart and many others. Food Safety Modernization Act The FSMA is the most sweeping reform of U.S. food safety laws in more than 70 years. It aims to assure the safety of food throughout the supply chain through the introduction of new requirements to food manufacturers, processors, transporters and distributors. There are seven foundational rules within the act with the most relevant rule being the "Sanitary Transportation of Human and Animal Food." The Sanitary Transportation rule applies to the US food chain as follows:  Shippers, receivers, loaders and carriers who transport food within the United States by truck or rail. Shippers in other countries who ship food to the United States by truck, rail, ship or air, and arrange for the transfer of the intact container onto a motor or rail vehicle for transportation within the U.S., if that food will be consumed or distributed in the United States. Companies involved in the transportation of food intended for export are covered by the rule until the shipment reaches a port or U.S. border. The rule does not apply to exporters who ship food through the United States (for example, from Canada to Mexico) by truck or rail if the food does not enter U.S. distribution.  Most shippers have until March of 2017 to comply with these new regulations. Companies with less than 500 employees have at least 1 additional year. For full FSMA compliance dates click here. While reefers are by nature temperature controlled, the new act requires that the shipper must be able to provide a log of the controlled environment upon request from the receiver or an auditor. These records must be kept for a period not exceeding 1 year. Orbcomm's existing ReeferTrak and ReeferConnect SaaS product provides a turnkey solution of hardware and software that is ready to address this market need. The FSMA is driving forward a wave of adoption ahead of the March 2017 deadline and Orbcomm is a major beneficiary. Some recent wins:  Aug 11th, 2016 - Northern Refrigerated to equip all reefers with Orbcomm solution by end of 2016  Aug 8th, 2016 - Carrier Transicold selects Orbcomm to build OEM telematics solution for Carrier.  July 19th, 2016 - Gulik Trucking selects Orbcomm for its refrigerated trucking fleets.   Dry Van Solutions Trucking companies also see benefits in tracking dry van trailers to give a global overview of their equipment and drivers. Orbcomm does not have a dominant position in the much larger dry van market but they do have a competitive turnkey solution (CargoWatch) with robust communications (dual cell/satellite) that integrate with leading trucking software such as TMWSuite and Loadmaster. Some recent wins:  August 25th, 2016 - L.J. Rogers Trucking Selects Orbcomm's Asset Tracking Solution for its Dry Van Trailer Fleet  August 3rd, 2016 - Barnes Transportation Selects Orbcomm's Trailer Tracking Solution for Its Dry Van Fleet  July 19th, 2016 - Gulik Trucking selects Orbcomm for its dry van fleet.   Orbcomm's introduction of an award winning solar powered trailer tracking device in 2015, the GT 1100, has been well received in the industry. The slim, ruggedized and easy to install GT 1100 has eliminated a number of barriers to broad adoption of this type of solution in the Dry Van business. Heavy Equipment Management and Telematics Orbcomm has achieved a dominant position in providing telematic solutions for mobile heavy machinery. Customers with Orbcomm's FleetView SaaS solution can have a near real time view of their entire fleet along with the information that is most important in maximizing the value of that asset. With heavy equipment often used outside the range of a cellular network, it makes a lot of sense to utilize Orbcomm's satellite or satellite/cellular solution in this market. The following marquee customers use an Orbcomm solution: Caterpillar, John Deere, Hitachi, Volvo, Hyundai Heavy Industries, Komatsu, Doosan, Terex. SCADA System Monitoring SCADA stands for Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition and is a commonly used acronym in the area of engineering controls. Up until this point, the Orbcomm solutions discussed generally relay data from the device (trailer, container, railcar) back to a central point on the internet. In this category, data is collected and commands are issued to a remote device to control its operation. Examples of this type of need are often found in the utilities industry. A pipeline may span thousands of miles and contain scores of pumping stations with pressure sensors, pumps and valves. These often span remote areas of the country where cellular connections are not an option. Using an Orbcomm solution pumps can be stopped and started, valves opened and closed, etc. In July of 2016, Orbcomm announced that it had won the "SMART Grid Product of the Year Award" for its dual-mode satellite-cellular solution which enables utility companies to manage their Smart Grids by monitoring and controlling reclosers and other network distribution devices in real time. Orbcomm allows you to connect anything that you wish to monitor or control anywhere on the planet in near real time. Utilities are a critical part of a nation's infrastructure so they are early adopters for this kind of technology. Inevitably the use of this type of solution will expand into other industries and find new use cases as the technology becomes cheaper. Automatic Identification System (AIS) AIS is a system that broadcasts a vessel's identification, position and other data. This system is mandated by the International Maritime Organization on all large vessels. While this system was initially designed with collision avoidance in mind, its use has broadened to include security, counter piracy, environmental monitoring, accident investigation (ala Costa Concordia), fishing zone compliance, port logistics and even analysis of shipping patterns as an indicator of economic strength. All Orbcomm satellites are AIS equipped and Orbcomm keeps increasing its AIS revenue each year. In Q2 of 2016, AIS revenue was up 36% Y/Y to $1.7M and will continue to grow due to a recent contract win by their reseller/partner LuxSpace Sarl to provide AIS data to the European Maritime Safety Agency. This 4-year agreement will start to add AIS revenue in Q4 of 2016. Although AIS sounds like an outlier from its core business, it is simply IoT applied to ships. In this case, Orbcomm primarily provides network services and others provide the devices and analytical applications. Why Buy Now? The chart below shows Orbcomm's share price since the company went public in November of 2006. 

 ORBC data by YCharts Compare the chart above to the typical Gartner hype cycle which accompanies many tech IPOs. The "Peak of Inflated Expectations" was in 2007, the "Trough of Disillusionment" around 2009 when investors realize it's not going to change the world overnight. 

 We have traveled along the "Slope of Enlightenment" and entered into the "Plateau of Productivity" which represents the point at which broad mainstream adoption of a new technology/solution is taking place. Orbcomm is a mature company with a strong product line that is ready to capitalise on a business segment that is in a transitional phase from early adopter to broad adoption. The FSMA ensures that food shippers and distributors move to an IoT solution and we will see a market segment (reefers) have full adoption over the next year or so. Orbcomm has a strong moat in its private satellite network that is designed specifically to handle M2M data. This unique asset allows Orbcomm to cover most of the earth and will make it a very strong contender for InterModal shipping allowing containers to be tracked from source to final destination regardless of cellular infrastructure. Orbcomm offers dual mode devices that support both satellite and cellular transmission. Orbcomm is laser focused on their business. They have been in the M2M business from the start and do not have to pivot to take advantage of the opportunity that IoT brings. The onset of IoT plays directly into their existing product portfolio and transforms the appearance of their business from niche satellite solutions player into mainstream IoT solutions provider. Orbcomm demonstrates a strong commitment to the bottom line. The two charts below show the relationships between SG&A and R&D expense in relation to annual revenue. SG&A cost as a fraction of annual revenue has shown a strong down trend whilst R&D has remained relatively flat at around 3.5% flat over the same period. 

 Fundamental Chart data by YCharts Orbcomm is a growing company with a 34% CAGR in revenues and 39% CAGR in EBITDA since 2011. This demonstrates a growing company which is also fiscally responsible. For more information on company history and financial metrics click here. An Acquisition Target? Earlier this month (Aug 1st, 2016) Verizon (NYSE:VZ) agreed to acquire Fleetmatics (NYSE:FLTX) for $2.4 Billion. Fleetmatics provides fleet management solutions based on cellular communications and had around 737,000 vehicles under subscription at the time of the deal. Click here for the WSJ article on this acquisition. In June 2016, Verizon agreed to acquire privately held Telogis, a specialized telematics company, for an unspecified amount. Click here for the story. If history is any guide, we will see aggregation of IoT players by larger well-established companies with deeper pockets. We used to have thousands of ISPs and telephone companies but those numbers dwindled quickly as they were acquired (usually at a premium) during the 1990s and 2000s. In the new frontier of IoT, we are likely to see the same pattern repeat as the industry behemoths stake their claims on the data landscape of the future. With a market cap around $725M and 1.65M subscribers, Orbcomm's valuation is $440/subscriber. By comparison, Verizon is paying $3,256 per subscriber for Fleetmatics. I'm not drawing a direct comparison between these two companies as Fleetmatics has a much stronger record of profitability and there are obvious synergies, but I do see these two companies as having a great number of similarities. The Future At its heart, Orbcomm is an Internet of Things company with a unique network offering that provides a strong competitive moat. The challenge in front of Orbcomm is one of scale. Orbcomm has recently added ~35,000 subscribers per quarter, excluding acquisitions. I believe the FSMA deadline will drive the new subscriber rate notably higher and we will see this reflected in the quarterly results between 2016 Q3 and Q1 2017. Orbcomm is operating marginally below profitability losing $2.1M in FY 2015 and $4.2M in the first half of FY 2016. I expect a strong increase in subscribers over the next 3 quarters which will put Orbcomm into a position of consistent quarterly profit. I believe the total addressable market for Orbcomm is in the tens of millions and the company is well positioned to capture a very significant share of this market before the end of the decade. 

Disclosure: I am/we are long ORBC. 
